-- в”Ђв”Ђ CORS-Tester в”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђ
UPDATE tools SET
  short_description = COALESCE($q$CORS-Tester refers to a category of free, web-based utilities that let developers check whether an API or web endpoint's Cross-Origin Resource Sharing (CORS) configuration is set up correctly. Representative tools include TestingBot's CORS Tester, Corsfix's CORS Tester, EaseCloud's CORS Tester, and CodeHappy's CORS Tester, which send preflight and actual cross-origin requests and report back the resulting CORS headers.$q$, short_description),
  pricing_model = COALESCE($q$Free to use, no account required$q$, pricing_model),
  starting_price = COALESCE($q$Free$q$, starting_price),
  founded_year = COALESCE(NULL, founded_year),
  company_size = COALESCE($q$Not publicly disclosed$q$, company_size),
  headquarters = COALESCE($q$Not publicly disclosed$q$, headquarters),
  languages = ARRAY[$q$English$q$]::text[],
  seo_title = COALESCE($q$CORS Tester: Free Tools to Check CORS Headers and Config$q$, seo_title),
  seo_meta_description = COALESCE($q$CORS Tester tools let you check if an API or site has valid CORS headers by simulating cross-origin requests. See how they work and where to find them.$q$, seo_meta_description),
  llm_readable_summary = COALESCE($q$CORS-Tester describes a category of free, browser-based diagnostic tools built to help developers verify whether a web server or API has Cross-Origin Resource Sharing (CORS) configured correctly. CORS is a browser security mechanism that restricts whether JavaScript running on one origin, meaning a specific combination of scheme, domain, and port, is allowed to make requests to a different origin. When a frontend application hosted on one domain tries to call an API hosted on another domain, the browser first checks the CORS headers the server returns before allowing the request to complete, and misconfigured CORS is one of the most common integration problems developers encounter when connecting a frontend to a backend API, particularly during local development or when adding a new client to an existing service. A CORS-Tester tool automates the process of checking this configuration without requiring the developer to write test code or dig through browser developer console errors. Typically, the user enters a target URL and specifies the origin that should be allowed to call it, along with the HTTP method (GET, POST, PUT, DELETE, and so on) and any custom headers the real request would send. The tool then issues the same preflight OPTIONS request and, in many implementations, the actual follow-up request that a browser would send, and reports back the CORS-related response headers, such as Access-Control-Allow-Origin, Access-Control-Allow-Methods, Access-Control-Allow-Headers, and Access-Control-Allow-Credentials, along with a pass or fail summary and often plain-language explanations of what is misconfigured. Several independent tools carry this name or serve this exact purpose. TestingBot offers a free online CORS Tester as part of its browser and API testing suite. Corsfix, a company focused on CORS proxy and debugging tooling, offers a CORS Tester that checks any URL for CORS configuration issues at no cost. EaseCloud provides a CORS Tester within its broader collection of free API and network tools. CodeHappy's CORS Tester allows testing by HTTP method and displays detailed header information along with troubleshooting tips. Other implementations include ToolDock's CORS Tester, which runs both the preflight and actual request from its own server and returns a plain-English pass or fail analysis, TestMu AI's (formerly LambdaTest) free CORS Tester, WebBrowserTools' Test CORS utility, and U2Tool's CORS Tester. All of these tools are free to use, require no registration, and are designed as quick diagnostic utilities rather than full API testing platforms. For a directory or SEO context, the practical value of these tools is straightforward: rather than reproducing a CORS error by trial and error inside a browser and reading raw console output, a developer can paste an endpoint and origin into one of these testers and get an immediate, structured answer about which specific CORS header is missing, misconfigured, or too permissive (a common security issue when an API returns Access-Control-Allow-Origin as a wildcard alongside credentialed requests). This makes CORS-Tester tools a common step in both frontend-backend integration debugging and basic API security review workflows, and they are frequently bookmarked by web developers alongside other free diagnostic utilities like DNS lookup, SSL checker, and HTTP header inspection tools.$q$, llm_readable_summary),
  status = 'published',
  noindex = false,
  sitemap_eligible = true,
  published_at = COALESCE(published_at, now()),
  updated_at = now()
WHERE id = '5389682a-e7f3-4c14-bf0a-6c92af78e8c5';

